  "abstract": {
    "sectionLabel": "Abstract",
    "paragraphs": [
      "Ultrasound-to-Speech aims to synthesize intelligible speech from tongue ultrasound video for silent speech interfaces. Prior systems rely primarily on convolutional or recurrent architectures and are typically evaluated using spectral distortion metrics that poorly reflect intelligibility. We introduce <strong>Tongue2Speech</strong>, a lightweight architecture combining explicit 3D spatio-temporal encoding with a multi-layer Transformer to model long-range articulatory dynamics.",
      "Evaluated on the English TaL corpus using ASR-based word error rate, <strong>Tongue2Speech</strong> achieves <strong>23.36% WER</strong> in single-speaker and <strong>31.64% WER</strong> in multi-speaker settings across six strong baselines. We further show that spectral MSE diverges from lexical accuracy, and that speaker-specific fine-tuning substantially restores intelligibility for unseen users."
    ],
